{"id": "page-00204", "type": "page_text", "source_file": "asm-handbook-v2.pdf", "page": 204, "text": "excluded from further consideration in this article. Among the alloys for which fracture toughness is a meaningful design-\nrelated parameter, controlled-toughness high-strength alloys and conventional high-strength alloys merit discussion.\nControlled-toughness high-strength alloys were developed for their high fracture toughness and range in\nmeasured K values from about 20 MPa m (18 ksi in ) upward. The alloys and tempers currently identified as\nIc\ncontrolled-toughness high-strength products include:\nTypical applications include 2419-T851 used in the lower wing\nskins of the B-1 bomber and 7475-T7351 and 2124-T851 in the\nF-16 aircraft.\nAlloy Condition Product form Conventional High-Strength Alloys. Although these alloys,\ntempers, and products are not used for fracture-critical\ncomponents, fracture toughness can be a meaningful design\n2048 T8 Sheet and plate parameter. Conventional aerospace alloys for which fracture\ntoughness minimums may be useful in design include 2014, 2024,\n2219, 7075, and 7079. These alloys have toughness levels that are\n2124 T3, T8 Sheet and plate inferior to those of their controlled-toughness counterparts.\nConsequently, toughness is not guaranteed.\n2419 T8 Sheet, plate, extrusions, and forgings\nControlled-toughness alloys are often derivatives of conventional\nalloys. For example, 7475 alloy is a derivative of 7075 with\nmaximum compositional limits on some elements that were found\n7049 T7 Plate, forgings, and extrusions\nto decrease toughness.\n7050 T7 Sheet, plate, forgings, and extrusions Fracture toughness quality control and material procurement\nminimums are appropriate for controlled-toughness, high-strength\nalloys, tempers, and products, because checks on composition and\n7150 T6 Sheet and plate tensile properties are inadequate assurances that the proper levels\nof toughness have been achieved. If the minimum specified\nfracture toughness value is not attained, the material is not\n7175 T6, T7 Sheet, plate, forgings, and extrusions acceptable.\nMinimum and typical room-temperature plane-strain fracture\n7475 T6, T7 Sheet and plate\ntoughness is listed for selected high-strength aluminum alloys in\nTable 10. The effect of alloying elements and microstructural\nconstituents on fracture toughness is discussed in the section \"Fracture Toughness and Fatigue Behavior\" in this article.", "has_tables": true, "num_tables": 1, "metadata": {}}
