{"id": "page-00344", "type": "page_text", "source_file": "asm-handbook-v2.pdf", "page": 344, "text": "Applications\nTypical uses. Electrical conductor wire, cooking utensils, appliances, and architectural applications. Medium strength\nand good resistance to corrosion are two characteristics of 5005 similar to those of 3003. When anodized, film on 5005 is\nclearer and lighter than on 3003 and gives better color match with 6063 architectural extrusions.\nMechanical Properties\nTensile properties. See Tables 52 and 53. Tensile strength and elongation are slightly lower in transverse direction\nthan in longitudinal direction.\nTable 52 Typical mechanical properties of alloy 5005\nTemper Tensile Yield Elongation Hardness(c), Shear strength\nstrength(a) strength(a) (a)(b), % HB\nMPa ksi MPa ksi MPa ksi\nO 124 18 41 6 25 28 76 11\nH12 138 20 131 19 10 . . . 97 14\nH14 159 23 152 22 6 . . . 97 14\nH16 179 26 172 25 5 . . . 103 15\nH18 200 29 193 28 4 . . . 110 16\nH32 138 20 117 17 11 36 97 14\nH34 159 23 138 20 8 41 97 14\nH36 179 26 165 24 6 46 103 15\n(a) Strengths and elongations unchanged or improved at low temperatures.\n(b) 1\n1.6 mm ( in.) thick specimen.\n16\n(c) 500 kg load; 10 mm diam ball\nTable 53 Mechanical property limits for alloy 5005 sheet and plate", "has_tables": true, "num_tables": 1, "metadata": {}}
